<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Mackenzie, Roderick. An Account of the Athabasca Indians by a Partner of the North West Company, 1795. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0032</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">N</span><sup>o</sup><span style="text-decoration:underline;"> 6</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">21</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">It is supposed that Greenland is joined to America &#8211; and we know that Spitzbergen, Nova-Zembla and Lapland, if not joined to each other, are not far distant &#8211; nor is it decided whether America is united to Asia or not &#8211; however the two Continents at Behring Straights are not far asunder, being in sight of each other.  What difficulty is there then in peopling the one Country from the other<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  All Savages lead a vagrant life, and think nothing of travelling a great distance &#8211; you will meet with an Iroquois from Montreal at the foot of the Rocky Mountain; and a Chipewean from Hudson Bay at the Bear Lake in Long<sup>e</sup> 125<sup>o</sup> So that these two Indians travel even if they went in a straight line from East to West no less than 168 Degrees to go to their respective homes; which we may double if we allow the adverse courses and lee way attending are Indian way of travelling and pursuits &#8211; this would make it 336 Degrees &#8211; almost the same as going around the World &#8211;</p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[21]</span></p>

